Kinematic and acoustic contributors to sensorimotor control of speech in Parkinsonâ€™s disease

Teja Rebernik

Generated on: Thu Sep 26 10:33:51 2024

The following R Markdown file shows model summaries and visualizations accompanying the analysis of acoustic and kinematic contributors to sensorimotor control of speech in Parkinsonâ€™s disease.

Due to the computing demands of generalized additive models, all models have been previously run and saved. The code used to generate them, however, is provided

#make binary smooths for assessing differences between groups

# for group distinction
adaptive$isPDf1 <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'F1')*1
adaptive$isPDf2 <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'F2')*1
adaptive$isPDttz <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'TTz')*1
adaptive$isPDttx <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'TTx')*1
adaptive$isPDtbz <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'TBz')*1
adaptive$isPDtbx <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'TBx')*1
adaptive$isPDjawz <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'LIz')*1
adaptive$isPDjawx <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'LIx')*1
 # for sex and group

adaptive$isPDf1F <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'F1' & adaptive$sex == 'V')*1
adaptive$isPDf2F <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'F2' & adaptive$sex == 'V')*1
adaptive$isPDttzF <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'TTz' & adaptive$sex == 'V')*1
adaptive$isPDttxF <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'TTx' & adaptive$sex == 'V')*1
adaptive$isPDtbzF <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'TBz' & adaptive$sex == 'V')*1
adaptive$isPDtbxF <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'TBx' & adaptive$sex == 'V')*1
adaptive$isPDjawzF <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'LIz' & adaptive$sex == 'V')*1
adaptive$isPDjawxF <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'LIx' & adaptive$sex == 'V')*1

adaptive$isPDf1M <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'F1' & adaptive$sex == 'M')*1
adaptive$isPDf2M <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'F2' & adaptive$sex == 'M')*1
adaptive$isPDttzM <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'TTz' & adaptive$sex == 'M')*1
adaptive$isPDttxM <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'TTx' & adaptive$sex == 'M')*1
adaptive$isPDtbzM <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'TBz' & adaptive$sex == 'M')*1
adaptive$isPDtbxM <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'TBx' & adaptive$sex == 'M')*1
adaptive$isPDjawzM <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'LIz' & adaptive$sex == 'M')*1
adaptive$isPDjawxM <- (adaptive$group=='PD' & adaptive$measure == 'LIx' & adaptive$sex == 'M')*1
# make sure data is ordered 

adaptive <- adaptive %>%
  arrange(measure, participant, trial)

# create new variable sex*measure
  
adaptive$MeasureSex <- paste0(adaptive$measure, "_", adaptive$sex)
adaptive$MeasureSex <- as.factor(adaptive$MeasureSex)

2.2 Differences between IwPD and CS

We ran two hypothesis-testing models: one with all participants and assessing all measures except TB, and one with a subgroup of participants for whom all sensors (including TB) could be placed.

#the following code has been used to run the model assessing differences between groups across all measures except TB

# m1_adaptive <- bam(z.value ~ s(trial, by=measure) + measure +

2.2.1 Visualization of the hypothesis-testing model

# Figure 2 (manuscript)

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot_smooth(m1_adaptive, view="trial", cond=list(measure="F1", isPDf1=1, isPDf2=0, isPDttz=0, isPDttx=0, isPDjawx=0, isPDjawz=0), rug=F, col="darkgoldenrod2", main="Change in F1 across trial", hide.label = T, ylim=c(-2,2), cex.axis=1, cex.lab=1, cex.main=1, ylab="F1 (z-normalized)", xlab="Trial")
## Summary:
##  * measure : factor; set to the value(s): F1. 
##  * trial : numeric predictor; with 30 values ranging from 1.000000 to 120.000000. 
##  * isPDf1 : numeric predictor; set to the value(s): 1. 
##  * isPDf2 : numeric predictor; set to the value(s): 0. 
##  * isPDttz : numeric predictor; set to the value(s): 0. 
##  * isPDttx : numeric predictor; set to the value(s): 0.

2.3 Overall effect of perturbation on the measures

The following two models assessed the effect of the adaptive formant perturbation on all measures, regardless of group

# m0_adaptive <- bam(z.value ~ s(trial, by=measure) + measure +
#             
#             s(trial, participant, by=measure, bs='fs',m=1) + 
#             
#             s(trial, targetWord, by=measure, bs='fs', m=1),
#             
#           data=adaptive_noTB, family="scat", discrete=T, nthreads=12)

m0_adaptive <- readRDS("m0_adaptive.rds")

2.4 Differences between male and female speakers

2.4.1 Visualization of the effect of sex

# Figure 4 (manuscript): Effect of sex on F1

par(mfrow=c(1,2))

plot_smooth(m2_adaptive, view="trial", cond=list(MeasureSex="F1_V", isPDf1F=1, isPDf2F=0, isPDttzF=0, isPDttxF=0, isPDjawxF=0, isPDjawzF=0, isPDf1M=0, isPDf2M=0, isPDttzM=0, isPDttxM=0, isPDjawxM=0, measure="F1", isPDjawzM=0), main="F1 across trial (female speakers)", ylim=c(-2,2), rug=F, col="darkgoldenrod2", ylab="F1 (z-normalized)", xlab="Trial", hide.label=T)
## Summary:
##  * MeasureSex : factor; set to the value(s): F1_V. 
##  * trial : numeric predictor; with 30 values ranging from 1.000000 to 120.000000. 
##  * isPDf1F : numeric predictor; set to the value(s): 1. 
##  * isPDf1M : numeric predictor; set to the value(s): 0. 
##  * isPDf2F : numeric predictor; set to the value(s): 0. 
##  * isPDf2M : numeric predictor; set to the value(s): 0. 
##  * isPDttzF : numeric predictor; set to the value(s): 0. 
##  * isPDttzM : numeric predictor; set to the value(s): 0. 
##  * isPDttxF : numeric predictor; set to the value(s): 0. 
##  * isPDttxM : numeric predictor; set to the value(s): 0. 
##  * isPDjawzF : numeric predictor; set to the value(s): 0. 
##  * isPDjawzM : numeric predictor; set to the value(s): 0. 
##  * isPDjawxF : numeric predictor; set to the value(s): 0. 
##  * isPDjawxM : numeric predictor; set to the value(s): 0. 
##  * participant : factor; set to the value(s): TRCS02. (Might be canceled as random effect, check below.)

  unique()%>%
  group_by(group, sex) %>%
  summarize(count = n())
